<DOC><DOCNO> AP890222-0189 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2357EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-SEC-ToysRUs     02-22 0135</FIRST><SECOND>AM-SEC-Toys R Us,130</SECOND><HEAD>Toys R Us Executive Surrenders Profits, Pays Fine in Insider TradingSuit</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Securities and Exchange Commission saidWednesday that an executive of Toys R Us Inc. agreed to settle civilinsider trading charges by repaying $35,000 in illegal profits and a$10,000 fine.   The commission had alleged that James M. Markham, former directorof industrial purchasing for the company, used advance knowledgethat the company's 1986 Christmas sales had jumped 27 percent over1985.   Markham purchased Toys R Us stock options before the salesfigures were announced publicly and then sold after theannouncement, the agency alleged in a complaint filed last Sept. 26.   In addition to the money penalties, Markham, without admitting ordenying his guilt, agreed not to violate securities laws in thefuture.</TEXT></DOC>